    "Learn about different types of breast cancer surgery, how they work, and what to expect during recovery.",
  author: "SixHealth Team",
  content: `
<div style="text-align:center; margin-bottom:20px;">
  <img 
    src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1550831107-1553da8c8464?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80&fm=webp&unique=1829"
    alt="Breast cancer surgery procedure"
    style="max-width:100%; border-radius:8px;"
  />
</div>

<p>
Surgery is one of the most common and effective treatments for breast cancer. The primary goal of surgery is to remove cancerous tissue from the breast and prevent the disease from spreading to other parts of the body. The type of surgery recommended depends on the size, stage, and location of the tumor, as well as the patient’s overall health.
</p>

<h2>Types of Breast Cancer Surgery</h2>

<h3>Lumpectomy</h3>
<p>
Lumpectomy, also known as breast-conserving surgery, removes the tumor along with a small margin of surrounding healthy tissue. The rest of the breast remains intact. This procedure is usually recommended for early-stage breast cancer and is often followed by radiation therapy to eliminate any remaining cancer cells.
</p>

<h3>Mastectomy</h3>
<p>
Mastectomy involves the removal of the entire breast. It may be recommended if the tumor is large, if there are multiple tumors, or if cancer has spread extensively within the breast tissue. Some patients choose mastectomy to reduce the risk of recurrence.
</p>

<h3>Lymph Node Removal</h3>
<p>
To determine whether cancer has spread, nearby lymph nodes may be removed and tested. A sentinel lymph node biopsy checks the first few lymph nodes where cancer is likely to spread. If cancer is found, additional lymph nodes may be removed.
</p>

<h2>Recovery and Side Effects</h2>
<p>
After surgery, patients may experience pain, swelling, and temporary limited arm movement. Recovery time varies but typically ranges from two to six weeks. Emotional support and follow-up care are essential parts of the healing process.
</p>

<p>
Surgical treatment plays a crucial role in breast cancer management and is often combined with other therapies such as chemotherapy, radiation, or hormone therapy for the best outcomes.
</p>
`
