  title: "Life After Breast Cancer Treatment",
  category: "Cancer Care",
  categorySlug: "cancer-care",
  description:
    "Learn what to expect after breast cancer treatment, including recovery, emotional healing, and long-term survivorship care.",
  author: "SixHealth Team",
  content: `
<div style="text-align:center; margin-bottom:20px;">
  <img 
    src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1576089541629-3ec6d7a28ba0?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80&fm=webp&unique=1837"
    alt="Breast cancer survivor after treatment"
    style="max-width:100%; border-radius:8px;"
  />
</div>

<p>
Completing breast cancer treatment is a major milestone, but survivorship comes with its own challenges and adjustments. Life after treatment often involves physical recovery, emotional healing, and long-term medical follow-up. While many patients feel relief and gratitude, it is also common to experience anxiety about recurrence or uncertainty about the future.
</p>

<h2>Physical Recovery</h2>
<p>
After surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy, the body needs time to heal. Fatigue may persist for weeks or even months. Gentle exercise, balanced nutrition, and proper sleep play a key role in rebuilding strength. Regular follow-up appointments help monitor recovery and detect any signs of recurrence early.
</p>

<h2>Emotional Well-Being</h2>
<p>
Emotional recovery is just as important as physical healing. Many survivors experience mood changes, fear of recurrence, or changes in body image. Support groups, counseling, and open communication with loved ones can help manage these feelings.
</p>

<h2>Follow-Up Care</h2>
<p>
Survivorship care plans usually include regular physical exams, imaging tests, and discussions about ongoing symptoms. Doctors may also recommend hormone therapy or targeted therapy for several years to reduce recurrence risk.
</p>

<h2>Healthy Lifestyle Changes</h2>
<ul>
<li>Maintain a balanced diet</li>
<li>Engage in regular physical activity</li>
<li>Avoid smoking</li>
<li>Limit alcohol intake</li>
<li>Manage stress through relaxation techniques</li>
</ul>

<p>
Life after breast cancer treatment is about rebuilding strength, confidence, and long-term health. With proper care and support, many survivors go on to live full and active lives.
</p>
`
