    id: "psoriasis-family-history-genetics",
    slug: "family-history-and-genetics",
    title: "Family History and Genetics in Psoriasis: Understanding Your Risk",
    category: "Psoriasis",
    categorySlug: "psoriasis",
    description: "Learn how genetics and family history influence psoriasis risk and severity.",
    author: "SixHealth Team",
    content: `
<div style="text-align:center; margin-bottom:20px;">
  <img 
    src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1489824904134-891ab64532f1?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80&fm=webp&unique=2191"
    alt="Genetic factors and inheritance"
    style="max-width:100%; border-radius:8px;"
  />
</div>

<p>
Psoriasis has strong genetic components with approximately 30-40% of patients having a family history. If one parent has psoriasis, children have roughly 10-15% risk of developing the condition. When both parents have psoriasis, risk increases to 50-60%. Genetic susceptibility combined with environmental triggers determines whether psoriasis develops.
</p>

<h2>HLA Genetic Association</h2>
<p>
Psoriasis is strongly associated with specific human leukocyte antigen (HLA) genes, particularly HLA-Cw6. HLA genes control immune system function, and specific variants predispose to psoriasis development. However, HLA testing is not routinely performed as presence doesn't guarantee disease development—approximately 10% of the general population carries HLA-Cw6 without developing psoriasis.
</p>

<h2>Multiple Gene Involvement</h2>
<p>
Psoriasis is a polygenic disease involving numerous genes, each contributing small effects. Over 60 genetic risk loci have been identified. Genes involved in immune regulation, particularly T cell function, are most relevant. Genes affecting skin barrier function, keratinocyte differentiation, and inflammatory pathways also contribute. The interaction of multiple genetic variants combined with environmental triggers determines disease development.
</p>

<h2>Environmental Triggers and Gene-Environment Interaction</h2>
<p>
Genetic predisposition alone doesn't guarantee psoriasis development. Environmental factors including infections (particularly streptococcal pharyngitis), stress, smoking, excessive alcohol, skin trauma, and certain medications trigger psoriasis in genetically susceptible individuals. The same genetic profile may manifest as psoriasis in one individual experiencing triggers while remaining dormant in another without trigger exposure.
</p>

<div style="text-align:center; margin-bottom:20px;">
  <img 
    src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1556228578-8c89e6adf883?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80&fm=webp&unique=2192"
    alt="Screening and prevention strategies"
    style="max-width:100%; border-radius:8px;"
  />
</div>

<h2>Family Screening and Prevention</h2>
<p>
Family members of psoriasis patients should be alert for early signs. Avoiding known triggers including infections, excessive stress, smoking, and excessive alcohol reduces risk. Maintaining skin health and treating skin injuries promptly help prevent trigger-induced disease onset. Genetic counseling helps families understand inheritance patterns and risk.
</p>

<h2>Disease Severity and Genetics</h2>
<p>
Genetic factors also influence disease severity and type. Family members may develop similar or different psoriasis manifestations. Early-onset psoriasis (before age 40) has stronger genetic influence than late-onset disease. Some genetic profiles predispose to aggressive disease while others tend toward milder manifestations.
</p>

<p>
Understanding genetic and familial factors empowers family members to recognize early signs and take preventive measures.
</p>
  `
