    description: "Understanding UVB and PUVA phototherapy for psoriasis treatment.",
    author: "SixHealth Team",
    content: `
<div style="text-align:center; margin-bottom:20px;">
  <img 
    src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506126613408-eca07ce68773?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80&fm=webp&unique=2201"
    alt="Light therapy treatment session"
    style="max-width:100%; border-radius:8px;"
  />
</div>

<p>
Light therapy (phototherapy) harnesses ultraviolet radiation to control psoriasis inflammation. Carefully controlled UV exposure reduces skin cell proliferation and suppresses immune activation. Phototherapy suits moderate psoriasis or extensive disease resistant to topical treatments and works particularly well when combined with other therapies.
</p>

<h2>UVB Phototherapy</h2>
<p>
Narrowband UVB (NB-UVB) is most commonly used. It penetrates skin, activating immunosuppressive pathways and slowing skin cell turnover. Patients typically receive 2-3 treatments weekly for 8-12 weeks, though duration varies. Each session lasts 15-20 minutes. Cumulative improvement occurs over weeks. Response rates are 75-80% in appropriate candidates.
</p>

<h2>PUVA Therapy</h2>
<p>
Psoralen plus UVA (PUVA) involves taking psoralen (light-sensitive medication) orally or topically, then receiving UVA radiation. PUVA is particularly effective for thick plaques and severe disease. Treatments occur 2-3 times weekly. PUVA requires more monitoring than UVB. Long-term PUVA increases skin cancer risk, limiting long-term use.
</p>

<h2>Targeted/Excimer Laser</h2>
<p>
Excimer laser delivers high-intensity UVB to localized lesions. It suits limited disease or specific problematic areas. Sessions are quick (minutes). Response is often rapid—plaques improve within weeks. Excimer suits patients who cannot access whole-body phototherapy or prefer targeted approach.
</p>

<div style="text-align:center; margin-bottom:20px;">
  <img 
    src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512621776951-1b1e6d8a6d6a?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80&fm=webp&unique=2202"
    alt="Dermatology clinic treatment"
    style="max-width:100%; border-radius:8px;"
  />
</div>

<h2>Side Effects and Monitoring</h2>
<p>
Common side effects include sunburn-like reaction, itching, and temporary redness. Eye damage is prevented through eye protection. Skin cancer risk is elevated with very high cumulative doses, particularly with PUVA. Regular skin cancer screening is recommended for long-term phototherapy patients. Cataracts may develop with inadequate eye protection during PUVA.
</p>

<h2>Phototherapy Maintenance</h2>
<p>
After achieving remission, maintenance therapy—reduced frequency—often continues. Some patients alternate phototherapy with other treatments to minimize long-term side effects while maintaining control. Starting phototherapy during winter takes advantage of lower natural UV exposure and seasonal improvement.
</p>

<h2>Combination Approaches</h2>
<p>
Phototherapy combined with topical medications often works better than either alone. Some systemic medications can be combined with phototherapy. Adding retinoids may enhance response.
</p>

<p>
Phototherapy provides effective control for moderate to severe psoriasis with good long-term safety profile when properly monitored.
</p>
  `
